metadata.name: Asemic Morphemes #5
metadata.description:
"Asemic Morphemes" is my second collection of asemic  writing. The first collection was “Asemic Writing 1o1”, which focused on letter placement and breaking the linear structures of writing.
In this collection, I have focused more on the structure of letters and morphemes.
According to the rules of this imaginary language, each morpheme consists of exactly three letters and the combination of all three letters together (48*48*48) creates 110,592 unique morphemes. The purpose of creating this collection is to challenge our understanding of the usual structures of human writing systems.

metadata.name: THE WORD AFTER US: An AI poetry unreading #40
metadata.description:
“Where in the world will words go, 
after us? How will they be arranged, 
and what will they sound like
when they arrive at their destination?
What will they be doing?
What will the world be doing?
Will the words be quiet or loud?
Will they be full of themselves,
or full of longing,
or full of longing’s opposite?”
 
An ars poetica on the future of literature and humanity. 
 
This project is a one-time generative poetry performance of a transhuman text by Sasha Stiles and her AI alter ego, Technelegy – read and unread by an algorithm authored by Nathaniel Stern. Every hash transforms one of 353 lines of AI-written poetry from legible letters into wordless language, generating a unique textblock from millions of possible combinations; each algorithmic translation unwrites itself, forever. Press "s" to overlay and toggle the original line of verse, and watch its shapes and meanings degenerate – or evolve – into an infinite visual poem.
 
All minters will receive an airdropped broadside (mp4) of the entire original poem after the performance is complete. A 1/1 media-rich audiovisual version of THE WORD AFTER US will also be made available.

 
Poetic traits:
- 353 possible lines of generative poetry produced by a GPT-3 language model fine-tuned on Stiles’ and Stern’s writing and research.
- 28 possible color palette combinations selected from Stern’s performative scanner art, with rare palettes including RGB, Hacker, Charcoal, and Chalkboard (black background).
- 6 possible fonts, including the premiere of Stern and Stiles’ custom AI font, NNFT (Neural Network Font Type), developed for their ongoing collaboration, “Mother Computer.”
- millions of layout and layering possibilities, including a rare “spiral” effect.
- billions of animation attribute combinations, which carry on forever.

metadata.name: ylb-mess-A #287
metadata.description:
With colors and shapes reminiscent of childhood LEGO explorations, 'ylb-mess-A' explores the assembly process in reverse, using recursive subdivision to create detailed structures instead of progressively building a complex structure brick by brick. Although the tools I use to explore and create have changed over the years, this piece reminds me of the natural creative curiosity that was instilled in me at an early age, for which I am incredibly grateful.

metadata.name: Bonsai Bonanza #882
metadata.description:
In previous works, I was attracted by the idea of ​​the domestication of plants.
According to Wikipedia, the purposes of bonsai are primarily contemplation for the viewer, and the pleasant exercise of effort and ingenuity for the grower. By contrast with other plant cultivation practices, bonsai is not intended for production of food or for medicine. Instead, bonsai practice focuses on long-term cultivation and shaping of one or more small trees growing in a container.
I pressume that the main intention is aesthetic. The beauty. Because we love beautiful things.
It is very interesting how we modify certain creatures for our sake of satisfaction.

May this collection brings you good fortune.

metadata.name: little god #244
metadata.description:
All of our strong emotions, feelings and experiences come from childhood. Sincere happiness or frightening cruelty is primarily inherent in children, so they learn about the world. When we were children, we first hurt someone, first burst into tears from resentment, learned what is good and what is bad. 
Our parents did not answer our questions, either because they did not know the answer or because they thought we were too young. We learned to look for the answers ourselves. Whoever says that children don't understand is a fool. They do understand, but they do it in their own way. The world as seen through the eyes of a child is not like the world as seen through the eyes of an adult. It is often not built on the laws of physics or the laws of the marketplace. In a child's world or universe, the moon is just a little light in the sky, and the next street is already a different country. Their world is built on speculation and magical theories. Unfortunately, a child's world is not eternal. As they grow up, the "real" life, the life of adults, pokes into them like a sharp needle over and over again. 
There is something incredibly tragic about this time gap between child and adult. It is this period that I wanted to trace in my work. As teenagers, it is as if we are between two trains, we are no longer children, but we are not yet adults. We get to know ourselves, we test our strength and readiness to exist in the "real" world. We are trying to find our place in the unfriendly world of adults, but we are also not ready to let go of the magic of childhood. It confuses, torments, and frustrates us. But it is a necessary and unavoidable tragedy. 

Code by PureSpider

metadata.name: Daydreamer #177
metadata.description:
‘For the artist communication with nature remains the most essential condition. The artist is human, himself nature; part of nature within natural space.’ (Paul Klee, 1944) 


Working on long-form nature has an interesting side effect. On the one hand, you're attempting a shallow imitation of a landscape.... You are working with cold logic and code, vainly trying to control randomness to create this virtual facsimile, something you know is artificial.... 

....and yet.... even with all this left-brain activity, your right-brain pushes back, and imagines being there. While working on this project I found myself continually daydreaming, wandering off to hear the sounds of waterfalls, or the crunch of walking along a sandy lake shore. If you've ever wondered about coding, I urge you to learn. Daydreams await....


Press '1' once rendering is finished, to redraw at 5120x5120 resolution 
Press '2' to export without post-processing effects 

3rd party libraries (license text and links included in source) 
- p5.js - Creative coding framework 
- JS Topology Suite "JSTS", a port of Java Topology Suite "JTS" - High-level Geometry library 
- WebGLImageFilter, Dominic Szablewski - phoboslab.org 

I have tried to use soft blurs and shadows to give a sense of layering and depth to the scene. After viewing for a while, it reminds me of 3D paper-art. There are traits for colour and amount of birds, waterfalls, etc. but none are especially rare – These properties are intended for filtering the collection.

metadata.name: Turbulence #449
metadata.description:
Swirly shapes are rendered by passes of poisson samples of a warped noise field. The noise shifts with each pass, creating a layered effect. 

Dense editions may take over 2 minutes to draw fully.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.

Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 928x1200px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume at any time during the drawing.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a not 1:1 variation of your edition at a resolution up to 3,000 px.

Common:
- 43 set palettes plus many more with combinations
- 3 color distribution methods
- 50/50 dark
- 50/50 monochrome with bright highlights 
- 3 drawing styles: lines, points, colored pencils
- 5 noises effects: full screen, distance from center, distance from bottom, horizontal center, vertical center, random circles, 3,5, or 7 horizontal and vertical bars
- Poisson point distribution based on set layers or the noise value

Rare
- 15% chance of a dark monochrome with gold strands

metadata.name: Abstract Attractorism #223
metadata.description:
Painted strange attractors in charcoal, acrylic, and colored pencils.

The piece has several phases: background, charcoal sketch, painting, finishing, and then starting over building up layers.

For each seed, the first painting is consistent for all platforms. Paintings after that may slightly vary between browsers. 

Press 'p' to pause and 's' to take a screenshot at any time. The image size is 1400x1082 which is the aspect ratio of a standard printer paper.

Features
- 200 possible palettes
- 3 possible color distribution methods
- 50% colored pencil border on completion
- Distribution of brush qualities and color variance from the palette colors

20% chance of rare
- More variation in the attractor functions for more unique results
- Small brush strokes with a longer paint time

10% chance of super rare
- Everything from rare
- Guaranteed large color blocks instead of smaller chaotic random color distribution
- Tape border when it's finished

metadata.name: Sand Table #256
metadata.description:
Just like a sand jar that you made or played with as a child. A recreation of layered colored sand with star glitter at the "peaks." Rare versions will be all gold and super rare has rainbow shimmer glitter.

Press 's' to take a screenshot. The image size is 1000x1000. 

Features
- 20 color palettes
- 2 color distribution methods
- 4 sand distribution methods
- sand size variation
- noise variables to determine patterns and layers

Rare features
- color sand with gold stars
- all stars instead of sand grains
- all gold glitter with silver stars
- all rainbow glitter with silver stars (super rare)

metadata.name: Fractured Cells #29
metadata.description:
Poisson disc sampling of a noise field masked to a shape, and then Voronoi tessellation. Rendered in hand-drawn lines.

Press 's' to take a screenshot. The image size is 1000x1000. 

Features
- 48 curated possible palettes
- 4 possible color distribution methods
- 3 possible shapes: one circle, random circles, circles distributed based on a quadtree 
- 1 to 3 levels of polygon smoothing
- polygon outlines
- polygon fill density and direction
- hand-drawn line roughness

Rare features
- 1 circle
- no polygon smoothing
- background polygons offset from foreground
- color distribution to have a "striped" appearance

metadata.name: Women in art #21
metadata.description:
According to Women Can't Paint, a book by Helen Gorrill, paintings made by men sell for 10x as much as women's paintings.

This piece is one of two conceptual generative artworks. One is called "Men in art", the other "Women in art". They are identical except for two differences:
1. The dithering filter in "Men in art" favors blue colors over red ones, while "Women in art" do the opposite.
2. The price of "Men in art" is 10 tez, while "Women in art" is priced at 1 tez.

Made with p5.js, Typescript and Fettepalette.

There is a secret key, which removes the dithering filter.
